AGI - On the second day of exercises around Taiwan, the Chinese armed forces have testified the ability to "take power", for retaliation in front of " separatist acts". A clear message for the new president of the rebel island who settled on Monday. The exercises, involving Chinese military units of the military air force, missile force, navy, army and coast guard, were announced yesterday morning, with maps showing five approximate target areas in the sea surrounding Taiwan.<br> The Chinese Ministry of Defense has emphasized that the exercises test the ability of the armed forces to occupy key areas, in line with Beijing's final goal to annex Taiwan.<br> &nbsp;
The Chinese Coast Guard accomplished "control exercises" off the eastern coast of Taiwan. Citing a Taiwanese security officer, Reuters reported that these exercises included "finte inspections" of civilian boats. The same official said that simulated attacks were also conducted against foreign ships in the Bashi Canal, which runs between Taiwan and the Philippines, and that about 24 war planes "joined" in Taiwan, but no one entered airspace, writes the Guardian.
&nbsp;
Yesterday armed missile combat aircraft had successfully carried out "mixed attacks" on Taiwanese military targets, but so far the exercises are smaller than those carried out in 2022 and 2023>. Beijing did not declare any flight interdiction zone and according to Taiwan's army no real ammunition was used except in areas of exercise on the Chinese mainland.
&nbsp;
China sent 19 warships around the perimeter of Taiwan, 16 ships of the coast guard and 49 war planes, of which 35 crossed the median line, the factual border between China and the island. In response, Taipei took off the planes, alerted its forces and moved anti-ship missile systems into coastal areas.<br> &nbsp;

