AGI -&nbsp; These are two German women, one Spanish and one Senegalese victims of the collapse in a local on the beach of Majorca. The teams of firefighters have explored the rubble in search of victims and survivors, but also of clues on the causes of the failure in which 16 people were injured.<br> The authorities, who declared three days of mourning, did not provide immediate indications on the causes, but said that the blame is probably of the excessive weight on the structure collapsed in the late afternoon of yesterday in the area of Playa de Palma, south of the capital of the Balearics.<br> Seven wounded are in "very serious" conditions and nine are severe injuries, reported emergency services. They were taken to several hospitals in Palma de Mallorca.
&nbsp;
The firefighters were deployed in large numbers, the ambulances brought the victims to the hospital and the road was closed by the police to allow rescue teams to work. A fireman, who described the scene as "a nightmare", told the newspaper 'Ultima Hora'&nbsp; that when the people arrived they cried and screamed around the rubble. The rescuers asked silence to hear the requests for help of those who were trapped under the rubble.
&nbsp;
The head of the firefighters of Palma, Eder Garcia, said that the floor of the building on the street level collapsed on a bar in the basement, and that's where the greatest number of victims were found. "The causes are under investigation. The first hypothesis is that perhaps it was due to excessive weight," he told journalists in Calle de Cartago, in front of the bay of Palma.
&nbsp;
Spanish Prime Minister Pedro Sanchez expressed his condolences on X to the families of the victims, stating "follow the evolution of the terrible collapse." The central government is ready to send "all the necessary resources" to help regional authorities cope with the situation, he added. The collapse of Thursday took place at the beginning of the high tourist season of the archipelago, on a seafront avenue that houses numerous shops and entertainment places. In 2009, seven people were killed in a three-story building in Palma de Mallorca, including three Colombians and two Germans.&nbsp;

