AGI - The landslide in a remote region in northern Papua New Guinea would have killed up to 100 people. These are the estimates of the residents, not confirmed by the local authorities. Six villages in Mulitaka, in the Porgera-Paiela district in the province of Enga, were overwhelmed by the landslide this morning at dawn.
&nbsp;
The landslide reportedly hit the village of Kaokalam in the province of Enga, about 600 kilometers (370 miles) northwest of Port Moresby, capital of the southern Pacific island nation, around 3 am local time. People in the surrounding villages Mulitaka said that 80-100 people could be buried, including children.
<div </div
The provincial administrator of Enga, Sandis Tsaka, said that ready-to-action teams were sent to the area, including humanitarian workers, police and health workers while assessing the extent of damage. "The devastating landslide, described as an unprecedented natural disaster, occurred in the early hours of this morning... causing substantial damage to property and human lives that are currently dispersed," said Tsaka.&nbsp;
&nbsp;

